{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1940"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1940"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.22,0.35,0.03,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1940"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by his partner with a three-day history of behavioural changes, including agitation and shouting. He also reports headache. He has no significant medical or psychiatric history and takes no regular medications. He does not use recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears confused and disorientated. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Two superficial oral ulcers are noted. Neurological examination reveals no nuchal rigidity, and Kernig and Brudzinski signs are negative. His blood alcohol level is 0.00.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain","Lumbar puncture","Intravenous aciclovir","Psychiatric assessment","Computed tomography of the brain"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of herpes simplex encephalitis, including acute behavioural changes, confusion, fever, headache, and oral ulcers. Herpes simplex encephalitis has a mortality rate of 70% if untreated, making it a medical emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous aciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E should be initiated immediately in cases of suspected herpes simplex encephalitis. Treatment should not be delayed while awaiting diagnostic confirmation, as early treatment significantly improves outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the brain is the most sensitive imaging modality for encephalitis and typically shows temporal lobe hyperintense lesions in herpes simplex encephalitis. However, obtaining imaging should not delay treatment initiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E with cerebrospinal fluid PCR is the gold standard for diagnosis. However, in the context of altered mental status, imaging to exclude raised intracranial pressure should precede lumbar puncture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychiatric assessment\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the initial management step given the presence of fever and confusion, which strongly suggest an organic cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E of the brain has poor sensitivity for early herpes simplex encephalitis but would be appropriate before lumbar puncture to exclude raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of confusion and fever in a young person should always prompt consideration of central nervous system infection. While various investigations are needed to confirm the diagnosis, the priority is to commence empiric treatment with aciclovir if herpes simplex encephalitis is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes simplex encephalitis requires immediate empiric treatment with intravenous aciclovir due to its high mortality if untreated.","Clinical features of herpes simplex encephalitis include personality changes, confusion, fever, and headache.","While imaging and CSF studies confirm the diagnosis, treatment should not be delayed while awaiting results."],"references":["Tunkel, A., Glaser, C., Bloch, K., Sejvar, J., Marra, C., Roos, K., Hartman, B., Kaplan, S., Scheld, W. and Whitley, R., 2008. The Management of Encephalitis: Clinical Practice Guidelines by the Infectious Diseases Society of America. Clinical Infectious Diseases, 47(3), pp.303-327.","Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {18 Jan 2025}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1940"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-18T16:09:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-18T16:10:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1940"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80236"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links"